content:
To test a modelâ€™s ability to make predictions, Einstein Discovery uses k-fold cross-validation. This process reduces sampling bias when validating a model.

Navigate to the Cross Validation Tab in Performance, click Model Evaluation, then Cross Validation.

Columns on the Cross Validation Tab:

Metric Name: Name of the metric.
Training Set: Metrics for the set of observations used to train the model.
Validation Set: Metrics for the set of observations used to validate predictions generated by the trained model.
Fold #1-Fold #4: Metrics for each fold.

Metrics on the Cross Validation Tab:

Number of rows: Total number of observations, or how many observations fell in that fold (approximately 25% of the entire dataset).
R2: Measures the model's ability to explain variation in the outcome.
MSE: Mean Squared Error, measuring the average squared error of predictions.
RMSE: Root Mean Squared Error, representing the square root of MSE.
MAE: Mean Absolute Error, measuring the absolute difference between actual and predicted values.
RMSLE: Root-Mean-Squared Logarithmic Error, comparing with RMSE.
Residual Deviance: Measures how well the developed model performs on your dataset.
Mean Residual Deviance: Measures how well the model performs on your dataset.
Null Deviance: Measures how well a simple model performs on your dataset.

Einstein Discovery conducts k-fold cross-validation (k=4) on your model, dividing observations into four separate partitions of equal size and conducting four test passes. For each fold, compile model metrics and take the average for an overall score.
title: Cross Validation Tab in Einstein Discovery
